> on 9/4/03 02:26, Richard Atwell related:


> >>
http://homepage.mac.com/ratwell/.Pictures/MoreParts4/109-DipstickLength.jpg

> hydraulic lifter cases have the partially blocked "well", on a solid case
> the area is open to the main sump volume. this is one of the subtle
> difference between solid and hydro cases, there are a few others as well,
> like the oil pickup tube is a different length.

> the easy way to check what kind of case you have is to look for the oil
> pressure overflow valve on the side of the case just above the lifter
bores,
> near # 1. there is a 14mm XZN screw head which is the cover for the valve.
> if you have this, you have a solid lifter case. hydraulic cases do not
have
> this valve.

I have a hydro case so I guess utill I pull the engine for the next rebuild
and split the case there is no way to make this cut out right?


> as for the temp readings, i can verify that with a 914 sump plate setup
> (with the short-nosed sender) in a hydraulic case, the oil temp readings
are
> very "lazy". the gauge still works, but it responds very slowly, taking a
> very long time to reach max temperature, and also taking a very long time
to
> go down if the temps go down. i have had the same sender setup in a solid
> lift case and the gauge reacts much more rapidly, as there is much greater
> oil flow in the region of the sender.


Without the cutout what would you suggest be the next best location for the
sender? Dipstick? I know they read to high but better that than to low. Do
you know if the dipstick sender reacts as quick as it should?


